node.text:
Page Sigband's home features a collection of wonderfully whimsical flea market art finds. “Our home is a collection of objects gathered from our travels, flea markets, estate sales and boutique shops. It’s a blend of Danish modern, tiki culture, Hawaiiana, surf, pop art, kitsch and Bauhaus.” ⁠
See more of this 1960's Eichler via the link in our bio.⁠
@designbypage⁠
⁠
Photo by Bret Gum @gum_and_gummer⁠

node.text:
You know what we’re fans of? Cool looking fans. Actually, increasing airflow in your mod home is a legitimate need. So changing out your old ceiling, wall and portable fans can upgrade the air circulation in any space, as well as provide an opportunity to add to your Mid Mod décor. Our friends at @matthewsfanco have a variety of eco-friendly, innovative and versatile options for some fun and unexpected atomic flair. Banish stale air with a retro-inspired wall mounted fan, or for larger spaces refreshing an older, generic ceiling fan for one that better fits the MCM vibe of your home.  Follow the tag or click the link in our bio to see more!⁠
#ad #advertisement #atomicranch #midcenturymodern #interiordesign #homedecor #midmod #aircirculation #modernfan #contemporaryfan #retrofan #retrodesign #midcenturyfan⁠

node.text:
Have you heard about Arapahoe Acres?⁠
Located just south of Denver, the stunning postwar neighborhood is home to butterfly roofs and low-slung, horizontal homes. Inspired by the iconic work of Frank Lloyd Wright, local businessman Edward Hawkins teamed up with architect Eugene Sternberg to design middle-class homes that were anything but middle of the road. Learn more about this post-war development via the link in our bio. ⁠
⁠
Photo courtesy of Cultural Landscape Foundation⁠
⁠

node.text:
The Fall Issue of Atomic Ranch is on sale now! Follow the link in our bio to order online or visit your local magazine retailer to get your copy today!⁠
⁠
This living area embodies open-concept living, espoused by architect W. David Mckinnie in Memphis, Tennesse. A built-in sofa anchors the room and is attached to the floating marble fireplace hearth. The soaring cathedral ceiling is original and untouched. ⁠
⁠
Photo by Michael Berry @lensman38104⁠
⁠

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Atomic Ranch on August 19, 2021. May be an image of outdoors and brick wall.

node.text:
North Towers of Denver Art Museum, designed by Gio Ponti. ”The facade belongs to the passersby,” Ponti wrote. “After all, architecture is made to be looked at.” The decorative shapes on the windows’ exterior embodies Ponti’s design philosophy advocating both function and ornamentation. The windows’ narrowness is due to the fact that artwork the museum houses needs to be protected from natural light’s damaging effects, and the hallways offered one of the few opportunities for windows. Learn more about Ponti and his remarkable body of work via the link in our bio. ⁠
⁠
Photo by BikeColorado/Flickr Commons.⁠
⁠

node.text:
Let's zero in on xeriscape. ⁠
This low-water, landscaping style does not have to mean just rocks and cacti, but strategically places plants closer to where you will see and enjoy them.⁠
Jim Coffman, president of Coffman Studio in Tempe, Arizona , shares his expert insight with us . Read his thoughts via the link in our bio. ⁠
⁠
Photo courtesy of Coffman Studio⁠

node.text:
Philmer J. Ellerbroek’s personal home in the Tustin foothills of Orange County, California, went on the market last year. After a few different homeowners gave it undesirable makeovers, it lost its charm. However, homeowner Casey Lesher’s dreamed of restoring it to its original beauty. See the stunning result via the link in our bio. ⁠
⁠
Photo by Chad Mellon @chadmellon⁠
⁠

This West Seattle neighborhood consists of bungalows and ‘war boxes’—a somewhat derisive term for boxy postwar tract homes—built between 1955 and 1965.
